<!-- NOTES TAB -->
<div class="tab-content active" id="notes-1-1">

  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>This section is pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Economics as a Social Science</h2>
    <p>Economics is a <strong>social science</strong> — it studies how people and societies interact to improve their economic well-being. Unlike natural sciences, economics deals with human behaviour, which is complex, diverse, and influenced by values and the surrounding environment.</p>
    <p>Economics draws on philosophy, politics, history, and psychology. Economic theories are based on logic and empirical data, using models to represent and analyse a complex reality.</p>
    <p>The discipline is divided into two broad branches:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Microeconomics</strong> — the study of individual consumers, firms, and markets</li>
      <li><strong>Macroeconomics</strong> — the study of the economy as a whole (growth, inflation, unemployment)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">The Nine Central Concepts</h2>
    <div class="key-terms">
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Scarcity</div><div class="definition">Unlimited human wants and needs cannot all be met by limited resources — the fundamental economic problem.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Choice</div><div class="definition">Because resources are scarce, individuals and societies must make choices about what to produce, how to produce it, and for whom.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Efficiency</div><div class="definition">Getting the maximum output from available resources without waste (productive efficiency) or producing the combination most valued by society (allocative efficiency).</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Equity</div><div class="definition">Fairness in the distribution of resources and outcomes — distinct from equality (equal shares).</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Economic well-being</div><div class="definition">The material and non-material quality of life available to individuals and societies.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Sustainability</div><div class="definition">Meeting today's needs without compromising the ability of future generations to meet theirs.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Change</div><div class="definition">The economic world is dynamic — conditions, technologies, and preferences constantly evolve.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Interdependence</div><div class="definition">Economic actors — households, firms, governments, financial sector, foreign sector — depend on each other in a complex web of interactions.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Intervention</div><div class="definition">Government or collective action to influence market outcomes, correct failures, or pursue equity and sustainability goals.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Scarcity and the Problem of Choice</h2>
    <p>Because resources are <strong>limited</strong> and human wants are <strong>unlimited</strong>, scarcity forces every society to confront three basic economic questions:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>What (and how much) to produce?</strong></li>
      <li><strong>How to produce it?</strong></li>
      <li><strong>For whom to produce it?</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Note: <strong>Free goods</strong> (such as sunlight or air) are not scarce in the economic sense — no choice is required to obtain them. Most goods, however, are <strong>economic goods</strong> that require resources to produce.</p>

    <h3>Factors of Production</h3>
    <p>Productive resources are grouped into four categories:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Description</th><th>Reward</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Land</strong></td><td>All natural resources — farmland, minerals, water, forests</td><td>Rent</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Labour</strong></td><td>Human effort, physical and mental, used in production</td><td>Wages</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Capital</strong></td><td>Man-made tools, machinery, and infrastructure used in production</td><td>Interest</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Entrepreneurship</strong></td><td>The ability to combine the other factors and bear risk to create goods and services</td><td>Profit</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Opportunity Cost</h3>
    <p>Every choice has a cost — the <strong>opportunity cost</strong> is the value of the <em>next best alternative</em> foregone when a decision is made.</p>
    <div class="callout exam-tip">
      <div class="callout-title">Exam tip</div>
      <p>Always express opportunity cost in terms of what is given up, not money spent. "The opportunity cost of building a new hospital is the schools that could have been built instead."</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Production Possibilities Curve (PPC)</h2>
    <p>The PPC (also called PPF) is a model showing the <strong>maximum combinations of two goods</strong> an economy can produce when all resources are fully and efficiently employed.</p>
    <p>Key features of the PPC:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Points on the curve</strong> — productively efficient (fully employed resources)</li>
      <li><strong>Points inside the curve</strong> — productively inefficient (unemployed or wasted resources)</li>
      <li><strong>Points outside the curve</strong> — currently unattainable</li>
      <li><strong>Negative slope</strong> — to produce more of one good, some of the other must be sacrificed (opportunity cost)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Increasing vs Constant Opportunity Cost</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Shape</th><th>Opportunity cost</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Concave (bowed out)</td><td>Increasing</td><td>Resources are not perfectly adaptable between uses — as more of one good is produced, progressively less suitable resources are reallocated</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Straight line</td><td>Constant</td><td>Resources are perfectly adaptable — each unit of one good always costs the same amount of the other</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Economic Growth and the PPC</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Actual growth</strong> — moving from inside the curve to the curve (using unemployed resources)</li>
      <li><strong>Growth in production possibilities</strong> — an outward shift of the entire PPC, due to more resources or better technology</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Economic Systems</h2>
    <p>Different societies answer the three basic questions in different ways. The main economic systems are:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>System</th><th>Who decides?</th><th>Key features</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Free market economy</strong></td><td>Price mechanism / private firms</td><td>Private ownership, profit motive, minimal government role</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Planned economy</strong></td><td>Government / central authority</td><td>State ownership, central planning, no price mechanism</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Mixed economy</strong></td><td>Both markets and government</td><td>Private sector alongside public sector; most real-world economies</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Circular Flow of Income</h2>
    <p>The circular flow model illustrates the interdependence between the key economic decision-makers: <strong>households</strong>, <strong>firms</strong>, the <strong>government</strong>, <strong>banks and the financial sector</strong>, and the <strong>foreign sector</strong>.</p>
    <p>In the basic model, households supply factors of production to firms, and receive income in return. Firms use these factors to produce goods and services, which they sell to households.</p>

    <h3>Leakages and Injections</h3>
    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="content-card">
        <div class="content-card-title">Leakages (withdrawals)</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Saving (S)</strong> — income not spent</li>
          <li><strong>Taxation (T)</strong> — income taken by government</li>
          <li><strong>Imports (M)</strong> — spending on foreign goods</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <div class="content-card-title">Injections</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Investment (I)</strong> — firm spending on capital</li>
          <li><strong>Government spending (G)</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Exports (X)</strong> — foreign demand for domestic goods</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>The economy is in equilibrium when total injections equal total leakages: <strong>I + G + X = S + T + M</strong>.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Economics studies scarcity-driven choice</li>
      <li>The four factors of production: land, labour, capital, entrepreneurship</li>
      <li>Opportunity cost = value of next best alternative foregone</li>
      <li>PPC shows maximum production with given resources</li>
      <li>Points on PPC = efficient; inside = inefficient; outside = unattainable</li>
      <li>Outward PPC shift = economic growth in production possibilities</li>
      <li>Circular flow: households and firms linked by factor and product markets</li>
      <li>Leakages: S, T, M — Injections: I, G, X</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- PRACTICE TAB -->
<div class="tab-content" id="practice-1-1">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Practice questions are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions</div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Define the term "scarcity" and explain why it forces societies to make choices.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Scarcity means that human wants and needs are unlimited while the resources available to satisfy them are limited. Because not everything can be produced, individuals and societies must choose which wants to satisfy and which to leave unmet — this is the fundamental economic problem.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. A government decides to build a new motorway. Explain what is meant by the opportunity cost of this decision.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          The opportunity cost is the value of the next best alternative use of those resources — for example, the hospitals, schools, or other public infrastructure that could have been built instead. Opportunity cost is always expressed in terms of what is foregone, not the financial cost.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. Using a diagram, explain the difference between a movement from inside the PPC to the curve, and an outward shift of the PPC.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <p>A movement from inside the curve to the curve represents <strong>actual growth</strong> — previously unemployed or underemployed resources are now being used efficiently. No new resources or technology are required.</p>
          <p>An outward shift of the entire PPC represents <strong>growth in production possibilities</strong> — the economy can now produce more of both goods. This occurs due to an increase in the quantity or quality of factors of production (e.g., more capital, better technology, larger workforce).</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">4. Identify and briefly describe the four factors of production.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Land</strong> — all natural resources used in production (farmland, minerals, water)</li>
            <li><strong>Labour</strong> — human physical and mental effort used in production</li>
            <li><strong>Capital</strong> — man-made resources used in production (machines, tools, factories)</li>
            <li><strong>Entrepreneurship</strong> — the ability to organise the other factors and take on risk to produce goods and services</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">5. Using the circular flow model, explain the difference between a leakage and an injection. Give one example of each.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          A <strong>leakage</strong> is income that flows out of the circular flow without becoming consumption spending — examples include saving, taxation, and import spending. An <strong>injection</strong> is spending that enters the circular flow from outside household consumption — examples include investment, government spending, and export earnings. When injections equal leakages, the economy is in equilibrium.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">6. Distinguish between a free market economy and a planned economy.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          In a <strong>free market economy</strong>, the three basic economic questions (what, how, for whom to produce) are answered by the price mechanism — private firms respond to consumer demand and the profit motive. In a <strong>planned economy</strong>, a central authority (typically the government) makes these decisions through central planning. Most real-world economies are <strong>mixed economies</strong> combining elements of both.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

